<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1708,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1708,1734]" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Variation.</emphasis>
Macropterous form individuals appeared occasionally in lab cultures. Hindwing is two times as long as forewing (
<figureCitation box="[298,422,1745,1771]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mirigryllus nigrus sp. nov. in living condition.A, hatchling; B, junior instar; C, D, penultimate instar; E, F, ultimate instar; G, male (macropterous); H, female (macropterous); I, male (brachypterous); J, female (brachypterous)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4443768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4443768/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Fig. 2G, H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1708,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1781,1807]" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Nymph.</emphasis>
Hatchling: Head brown, body yellow and legs pale (
<figureCitation box="[886,977,1781,1807]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mirigryllus nigrus sp. nov. in living condition.A, hatchling; B, junior instar; C, D, penultimate instar; E, F, ultimate instar; G, male (macropterous); H, female (macropterous); I, male (brachypterous); J, female (brachypterous)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4443768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4443768/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Junior instar: Brown to black. Band between lateral ocelli appeared (
<figureCitation box="[969,1057,1817,1843]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mirigryllus nigrus sp. nov. in living condition.A, hatchling; B, junior instar; C, D, penultimate instar; E, F, ultimate instar; G, male (macropterous); H, female (macropterous); I, male (brachypterous); J, female (brachypterous)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4443768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4443768/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Penultimate instar: Total black. Length of ovipositor in dorsal view as long as one abdominal segment (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mirigryllus nigrus sp. nov. in living condition.A, hatchling; B, junior instar; C, D, penultimate instar; E, F, ultimate instar; G, male (macropterous); H, female (macropterous); I, male (brachypterous); J, female (brachypterous)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4443768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4443768/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Fig. 2C, D</figureCitation>
). Ultimate instar: Total black. Length of ovipositor in dorsal view as long as 2–3 abdominal segments (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[326,1262,181,1942]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Mirigryllus nigrus sp. nov. in living condition.A, hatchling; B, junior instar; C, D, penultimate instar; E, F, ultimate instar; G, male (macropterous); H, female (macropterous); I, male (brachypterous); J, female (brachypterous)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4443768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4443768/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Fig. 2E, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1708,2023]" box="[199,886,1997,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1997,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">Etymology.</emphasis>
Species name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="He &amp; Shen &amp; Wu &amp; Chen &amp; Li" authorityYear="2020" box="[501,573,1997,2022]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Mirigryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrus">
<emphasis box="[501,573,1997,2022]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="118">nigrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
means its black body color.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,150,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,482,150,177]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">Measurements (in mm).</emphasis>
Male: body length 13.62–14.08, pronotum length 2.60–2.81, hind femur length 8.63–9.16, hind tibiae length 6.46–6.63, forewing length 4.66–4.90.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,150,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">Female: body length 14.20–15.53, pronotum length 2.81–3.01, hind femur length 8.55–9.19, hind tibiae length 6.20–6.51, forewing length 4.77–6.99, ovipositor length 6.97–7.55.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,150,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,276,294,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">Songs.</emphasis>
The calling song was about 8.63 cycle/min. Each cycle contained 12–16 pulses in 0.165± 
<geoCoordinate box="[1301,1374,294,321]" degrees="0.013" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="119" precision="55" value="-0.013">0.013s</geoCoordinate>
from weak to strong (
<figureCitation box="[331,401,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,200,1601]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1614]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Calling song of Mirigryllus nigrus. Wave of songs with 1s and 0.1s scale bar." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4443772" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4443772/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,150,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,366,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="119">Life cycle.</emphasis>
As we found many hatchlings in August, combined the adult appearance date, we infer that this species is univoltine with adult appeared from May to July and nymphs overwinter.
</paragraph>
